definition.value: An L-cysteinyl ester resulting from the formal condensation of the carboxylic acid group of L-cysteine with methanol. It is used (as the hydrochloride salt) as a mucolytic for the treatment of respiratory disorders associated with productive cough.
An N-acyl-beta-D-galactosylsphingosine having a sulfo group at the 3-position on the galactose ring and (15Z)-tetracos-15-enoyl as the N-acyl group.
A chromanol that is chroman-6-ol which is substituted at positions 2, 3, and 4 by p-(2-pyrrolidin-1-ylethoxy)phenyl, p-hydroxyphenyl, and methyl groups, respectively (the 2R,3R,4S diastereoisomer).
An enal consisting of propene having a formyl group at the 1-position.
A medium-chain fatty acyl-CoA that results from the formal condensation of the thiol group of coenzyme A with the carboxy group of (pentylsulfanyl)acetic acid.
A pyrroledicarboxylic acid that is pyrrole-2,5-dicarboxylic acid in which the hydrogens at positions 3 and 4 have been replaced by indol-3-yl groups.
A cysteine derivative consiting of L-cysteine carrying an S-oxy-substituent.

A 3beta-hydroxy-Delta(5)-steroid that is desmosterol in which the double bond at position 24-25 has been oxidised to the corresponding epoxide (the 24S diastereoisomer). It is an oxysterol agonist of the liver X receptor.
A member of the class of pyrazoles that is 1H-pyrazole carrying 1,4-benzodioxane-6-yl and 5-ethyl-2,4-dihydroxyphenyl substituents at positions 4 and 5 respectively.
A cyclohexanedione carrying oxo substituents at positions 1 and 2.

An organic chloride salt that is the monochloride salt of crystal violet cation. It has been used in creams for the topical treatment of bacterial and fungal infections, being effective against some Gram-positive bacteria (notably Staphylococcus species) and some pathogenic fungi (including Candida species) but use declined following reports of animal carcinogenicity. It has also been used for dying wood, silk, and paper, as well as a histological stain.
A non-proteinogenic L-alpha-amino acid that is L-methionine in which one of the hydrogens attached to the amino group bas been replaced by a carboxy group.
A glucopyranose ring with a phosphate replacing the hydroxy in the hydroxymethyl group at position 6.
A cysteine derivative consisting of L-cysteine carrying an S-hydroxy-substituent.
A cysteine derivative consiting of L-cysteine carrying two S-oxy-substituents.
A cellotriose with a alpha-configuration at the anomeric position.
